An Abundant Number (also called an excessive number) is a number for which the sum of its proper divisors is greater than the number itself.

Proper divisors of a number are all positive divisors excluding the number itself.

For example:

12 → Proper divisors: 1, 2, 3, 4, 6 → Sum = 16 → 16 > 12 → Abundant Number

10 → Proper divisors: 1, 2, 5 → Sum = 8 → 8 < 10 → Not Abundant

Write a program to check whether a given number is an abundant number or not.

Input Format

A single positive integer N.

Constraints

1 ≤ N ≤ 10⁶

Output Format

Print "Abundant Number" if the number is abundant, otherwise print "Not an Abundant Number".

Sample Input 0

12
Sample Output 0

Abundant Number
Sample Input 1

10
Sample Output 1

Not an Abundant Number

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <math.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {

   int n, sum=0;
    scanf("%d", &n);


    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        if (n % i == 0) {   // check if i divides n
            sum+=i;
        }
    }
    if(sum>n)
       printf("Abundant Number");
    else
       printf("Not an Abundant Number");
}

